Aadhaar-Linkage Microservice
Data Source: 
1. Aadhaar Data (UIDAI)
The Unique Identification Authority of India (UIDAI) maintains a minimal set of demographic and biometric data for each Aadhaar number holder. The UIDAI's policy strictly prohibits collecting sensitive personal information.
Key Data Fields:

Aadhaar Number: A 12-digit unique identification number.


Name: The full name of the individual.


Date of Birth: The person's date of birth.


Gender: The person's gender.


Address: The residential address.


Parent/Guardian Name: Required for children.


Mobile Number: (Optional)


Email ID: (Optional)

2. PAN Data (NSDL)
The Permanent Account Number (PAN) is a ten-character alphanumeric identifier issued by the Income Tax Department. The data collected is primarily for tax and financial purposes.
Key Data Fields:

PAN Number: The 10-character alphanumeric PAN.


Name: The full name of the individual (first, middle, and last names).


Father's Name: Mandatory, even for married women.


Mother's Name: (Optional)


Date of Birth: For individuals, or Date of Incorporation/Formation for other entities.


Gender: For individual applicants.


Address: The communication address (residence or office).


Telephone/Mobile Number:


Email ID:


Aadhaar Number: Often linked to the PAN.

3. Voter ID (ECI)
The Voter ID (officially the Electoral Photo Identity Card or EPIC) is issued by the Election Commission of India (ECI) for voting and serves as a general identity, address, and age proof.
Key Data Fields:

Voter ID Number (EPIC Number): A unique alphanumeric number.


Name: The voter's name.


Relative's Name: The name of a chosen relative (e.g., father or mother).


Photograph: The voter's picture.


Age: The person's age.


Address: The home address of the voter.


Electoral District: The district the voter is registered in.


Assembly Constituency: The constituency the voter belongs to.


Part Number: A number to help locate the voter on the electoral roll.

4. Driving License (Sarathi/Parivahan)
The driving license is managed by the Ministry of Road Transport & Highways, with the Sarathi portal handling driver-related services.
Key Data Fields:

Driving License Number: A unique alphanumeric license number.


Name: The full name of the license holder (first, middle, and last).


Date of Birth: The date of birth.


Address: The residential address.


Issue Date: The date the license was issued.


Expiration Date: The date the license expires.


License Class: The type of vehicle(s) the person is authorized to drive (e.g., motorcycle, car, heavy vehicle).


Gender: The person's gender.


Height: The person's height.


Blood Type: (Optional, often a fillable field).


Photograph: A photo of the license holder.

Project Goal:
 To build a robust Spring Boot microservice called aadhaar-linkage-service that acts as a central hub for managing and linking personal identity data across various Indian data sources. The service's primary function is to maintain a single, unique AadhaarLinkageKey (ALK) for each individual, associating it with data from sources like Aadhaar, PAN, Voter ID, and Driving License.

Core Business Logic & Rules:


Primary Key: The AadhaarLinkageKey
(ALK) is the definitive identifier for a person within our system. It is a system-generated, unique key.


Data Matching for Linking: The service will use
a combination of PII fields (foreName, secondName, lastName, DOB, Aadhaar Number, and an optional Address) to search for an existing person record in the database.


Idempotent & Reference-Based Linking: If a person's
data is submitted from a new data source (e.g., PAN), the service will search for an existing record. If found, it will assign the same ALK to the PAN data and increment the counter for the PAN data source. If no match is found, a new ALK will be created, and
the counter for the originating data source will be set to 1.


Controlled Deletion: A person's record can only
be permanently deleted when all associated data source counters are 0.


Secure & Immutable Updates: An update of a person's
PII does not modify the existing record. Instead, it creates a new record with a new AadhaarLinkageKey.
The counter on the old record, for the source that initiated the update, is then decremented.


Single-Point API: All actions (Insert, Update,
Delete) will be handled by a single, intelligent API endpoint using an action
field in the request payload.

 
 
